@incollection{Voigt2013,
abstract = {Theory about the relevance of soft law abounds; empirical research on the topic does not. This study begins to even out this imbalance by not only developing a number of conjectures based on institutional economics, but also by testing them empirically. Based on all 2,289 soft laws concluded by the United States between 1981 and 2010, I find the following. (1) the number of international agreements increased dramatically between the mid 1990s until around 2006; since then, however, their use has declined almost as dramatically. (2) Around two-thirds of all international agreements concern only three policy areas: the military, science and technology, and aid. (3) More than 90{\%} of all iinternational agreements are conducted bilaterally. (4) Some 40 percent of these agreements are concluded by a non-traditional actor on the U.S. side, i.e., an actor other than the President of the secretary of state.},
annote = {"Theory about the relevance of soft law abounds; empirical research on the topic does not. This study begins to even out this imbalance by not only developing a number of conjectures based on institutional economics, but also by testing them empirically. Based on all 2,289 soft laws concluded by the United States between 1981 and 2010, I find the following. (1) the number of international agreements increased dramatically between the mid 1990s until around 2006; since then, however, their use has declined almost as dramatically. (2) Around two-thirds of all international agreements concern only three policy areas: the military, science and technology, and aid. (3) More than 90{\%} of all iinternational agreements are conducted bilaterally. (4) Some 40 percent of these agreements are concluded by a non-traditional actor on the U.S. side, i.e., an actor other than the President of the secretary of state."

Theoretical paradigm used to separate hard from soft-law - procedural criteria. If it was ratified it is Hard law, if it was not it is soft-law.

The theoretical framework Voigt used to assess the choice between hard and soft law was two-fold. (i) the individual decision-making is assessed under the light of institutional economics and transaction-cost economics; (ii) the strategic interaction is assessed through the lenses of game-theory.

Transaction cost analysis

(a) Relevant transaction costs in international lawmaking


(1) Negotiation costs - Cf {\textgreater} Ci
(2) Ratification costs - Cf {\textgreater} Ci
(3) Monitoring costs - Cf {\textless} Ci ( because formal cooperation allows for cost-sharing in the monitoring)
(4) Enforcement costs - Cf {\textless} Ci (idem; plus: the larger publicity allows for reputational and domestic enforcement to occur IMPORTANT!)
(5) Modification costs - Cf {\textgreater} Ci
(6) Exit costs - Cf {\textgreater} Ci

All things equal, rational lawmakers will prefer informal institutions if neither (i) monitoring, and (ii) enforcement problems exist

(b) governance structure-related costs

Now we turn to the relevant "governance structure costs", since, as seen before, hierarchical structures of governance (in our case Hard-law) may make sense if (i) TC are high and the (ii) governance "structure" costs are also low. Otherwise there may be no net benefits from curbing those TCs.

The determinants of "governance structure costs"

(1) frequency of interaction (function of geography, externalities etc.).

(2) Degree of asset specificity (Hold-up risk...)

(3) degree of uncertainty

Transaction cost-based conjectures:
(i) low frequency of interaction and asset specificity ought to lead to less formality; (ii) whereas high frequency and asset specific enforcement ought to lead to more formal law; (iii) finally, where there are high degrees of asset specificity, uncertainty will matter, and so one would expect increases in formality. 

Game theoretical analysis

Conjectures:

H1) IIL ought to be expected more often in coordination games, whereas FIL in mixed-motive games

H2) Repeat pplayers are more likely to resort to IIL (potential for tit for tat...)

H3) Given the lack of publicness it is unlikely to govern situations where the underlying pay-off structure is that of a prisoners dilemma

H4) States will prefer FIL if they are interested in improving their reputation (alternative: high reputation, all things equal, more IIL)

H5) Due to increasing monitoring costs, IIL is likely to be agreed upon among small numbers of participants

H6) Politicians will prefer informal over more formal law if the agreement will be unpopular among its constituents (ISSUE SALIENCE!!!). The rationale being the lower the issue-salience the lower thedomestic audience costs + lower expected losses in terms of rent-seeking.

H7) Incumbetn will prefer FIL if it expectes loosing the elections. Rationale: tying hands mechanism (see e.g. Moravcsik 2000).

A weekness pointed out by professor voigt is that the decision on the institutional-choice must always be incentive compatible with all parties. He thus proposes that future work should give more attention to bargaining theory. [A potentially relevant variable may be power...in coordination games the powerfull parties are expected to be able to set the agenda...ver melhor).

Data

There is no world-wide available data on the collection of such agreements and, furthermore, many countries do not even keep track of them.. To curb this they focused on informal agreements concluded by the US. Due to the "Case-Zablocki act of 1917", which prescribes the department of states reporting all IAs to congress no later than 60 days after entering into force. (N= 2,289). Exempted were: (i) militery-related agreements; (ii) classified material; (iii) irrelevant coordination games; (iv) bilateral assistance for narcotics and relatively similar criminal behaviour.

Domestic politics conjectures

States deal with informal international law in different ways. In germany the ministry in charge of the cooperative effort shoudl always "before international law treaties are elaborated and concluded, the ministry in charge must check whether a binding contract under international law is irrefutable or whether the same goal may also be attained through other means, specially through understandings which are below the threshold of an international agreement". In France, however, these agreements ought to be exception and only resorted to in particularly uncertain circumstances. What explains these variations?

H1) The higher the number of players that need to consent to ratify formal international law domestically, the higher the proportion of informal law. [this argument applies to hard v. soft but not necessarily to public v. secret).

H2) The higher the required majorities needed to ratify FIL, the higher the proportion of informal law.

H3) The higher the degree of ideological heterogeneity among the veto players, the higher the proportion of informal law.

H4) The more costly it is to abolish formal treaty law (in terms of the number of players who have to consent and/or the required majorities), the higher the proportion of informal law.

H5) Countries in which formal international law assumes supremacy over domestic law will pass relatively less formal international law than countries in which the inverse holds, ceteris paribus.

H6) If the domestic judiciary has the power to apply formal international law directly, a higher proportion of informal law will be used than in countries in which the direct application is not possible.

H7) presidential systems will resort more often to informal law than will parliamentary systems. ( Rationale: the executive passes a great deal of informal law, i.e. “legislates” without the legislature's approval and sometimes without the legislature even being informed of it (either before international agreements are concluded or even after), the legislature may have an incentive to change this state of affairs).

H8) legislatures under presidential systems are more likely to pass legislation aimed at monitoring informal law making than are legislatures under parliamentary systems.

H9) Governments under MR systems are more likely than governments under PR systems to draw on informal law because agreements are less visible

H10) ((a) The longer a country has been sovereign, the higher the propensity of its government to resort to informal law.
(b) The longer a country has been democratic without interruption, the higher the propensity of its government to resort to informal law.

Particularly relevant for Part I of the thesis!!!! See page 11!!

Voigt seems to recognize the potential for the "retaliatory-disclosure" mechanism to induce compliance. Because part of the benefits of doing an informal agreement stemm from its secrecy and unorbservability, then given the value of secrecy it may be used to deter defection. In the absence of a central enforcement authority contrats tended to be enforced by the exchange of collateral or hostages (Kronman 1985). Voigt mentions that because the instrument if disclosed leads to high costs then it may be seen as an "hostage". If one of the parties decides to defect, the other may threaten to "destroy the hostage". The problem with the "hostage exchange metaphor" is that it is not clear why such a threat would be credible. After all, the other party also engaged in it and would also thus suffer reputational costs too.

Results

(1) Informal international law making did increase dramatically until around 2006. Since then, its use has declined almost as dramatically. (2) Around two-thirds of all international agreements are concerned with only three policy areas: the military, science and technology, and aid. (3) More than 90{\%} of all international agreements are conducted bilaterally. (4) More than 40 percent of all agreements are concluded by a non-traditional actor on the U.S. side, i.e., an actor other than the president or the secretary of state.

Future agenda for research

(1) what are the central characteristics of these agreements that could be described in more detail? Design of renegotiation rules, sunset clauses, enforcement mechanisms...

(2) Are these agreements equally as likely to be complied with as FIL or are there systematic differences?

(3) Cross-country analysis of two main questions: (i) the same hypothesis accross coutry? (ii) variations in the institutional set-up for monitoring IIL

(4) Model bargain dynamics in the institutional-choice? [variation on the valuation for secrecy and cooeperative benefits!!! + Power asymmetries!!!]

(5) determinants of IILawmaking by IOs},
