@article{Tallberg2014i,
annote = {1) Why it matters

TNA participation in IOs varies accross time and IOs. This article attempts to understand this phenomena by theoretically analyzing transparency as institutional-design. The theoretical conjectures will then be tested through  a dataset of formal TNA access in 298 organizational bodies from fifty IOs.

Centran results: (i) TNA participation in IOs increased over the past sixty years in all IOs and across issue area; (ii) variation in TNA access seems to be driven by a combination of three factors:  functional demand for resources of TNAs, domestic democratic standards, and state concerns with national sovereignity; (iii) existing research suffers from a slection bias that has led it to overestimate the general importance of a new participatory norm in global governance for the openness of IOs.

