Summary

Main research questions: (i) why would states engage in the high sovereignity costs of allowing TNAs to participate in international decision-making? (ii) what explains the dramatic increase in TNA participation in the last years? (iii) what accounts for the variations in IO-access by TNAs?

The theoretical starting point is that they conceive TNA access as a dimension of the institutional design of IOs. Access is different from participation, where the latter, for them, means only presence, and the former means participation in policy-making and its implementation. Importante: It should be noted, however, that in our theoretical framework of transparency as access to compliance-relevant information, mere presence may matter; if by just being there the TNAs obtain access to such information they may diffuse it thus potentially raising reputational and dometic audience costs.

The dataset

The selected IOs (50) make a stratified random sample. The sample was drawn from the Correlates of war IGO dataset. To be included in the sample the IOs must: (i) be intergovernamental; (ii) be budgetary, decision-making, and reporting, indepent from other IOs; (iii) have at least three members; (iv)  have at leaston organizational body that operates permanently; (v) and be active in 2010 (???).
