b) Their argument: functional demand, domestic democracy, and state sovereignity

The rational functionalist explanatory dimension focuses on the demand for TNA participation due to the expected benefits it may provide. In particular, it argues that the IO bodies will resort to TNAs where they lack the resources or expertise needed for a certain relevant task. The advantages of TNAs ought to be more pronounced in policy areas which are (i) technically complex, require local implementation, and present significant non-compliance incentives, and where compliance information is held by societal actors (or at least in a more cost-effective manner). The rationale being that TNA are generally experts on the policy issues that most concern them (and the information they provided is for free) which will be particularly relevant in areas with technical complexity or uncertainty about the state of the world, are better positioned to implement policy at the societal level, and have unique access to grassroots information on state violations.

