@article{W.Abbott2000,
abstract = {Allgemein zu hard law vs. soft law - 421 bis 423 zu referenzieren; dort auch teilweise zu den Vor- und Nachteilen von hard und soft law},
annote = {Why it matters? 
The international system, and its relations, is extremely legalized. However, one finds heterogeneous levels of “legalization” varying across regimes. This paper represents one of the first attempts at theorizing the “why” that is so. 
Research questions? 
  
{\textperiodcentered}         What explains institutional-choice, hard v. soft, in international legalization? 
  
Main takeaway? 
  
a)      What is the hard- v. soft-law continuum? 
In traditional legal terms hard-law refers to legally binding instruments of international law, treaties, and soft-law to non-binding agreements, such as informal agreements, (most) exchanges of letters etc. However, the authors of this article do not follow these procedural binary criteria, focusing in functional variables. 
The term hard law stands for (i) legally binding obligations that are (ii) precise and that (iii) delegate authority for interpreting and implementing the law; and soft law should stand for the opposite. Yet, contrary to the preceding literature, their continuum is not binary but rather composed by the three above continuous variables. And so the instruments are not just hard or soft, but can be one of the many values in the spectrum. 
To characterize these continuum they resort to three variables: (i) “O” referring to the level of obligation, (ii) “P” precision of the provisions; and (iii) “D” degree of delegation. Varia- tions along each dimension are indicated by capital letters for high levels (for example, O), small letters for moderate levels (for example, o), and dashes for low levels (-). Thus, [O,P,D] or [O,p,D] constitute hard law, and [-,-,-] will be on the opposite of spectrum, in between one may find [o,P,-] for example, meaning moderate obligation, high precision and low delegation. 
b)      Endogeneizing institutional-choice 
Advantages of Hard-law 
1.      Credible commitments 
Given the “anarchical” structure of the international system, states have a hard-time decoupling true-revealed preferences from cheap-talk which leads to (ex ante) transaction-cost enhancing uncertainty regarding preferences. Similarly, states cannot observe the behaviour of others which leads to uncertainty regarding behaviour. If these uncertainty-based transaction costs are high enough they may trump the expected benefits of cooperation and lead to non-cooperative behaviour. The expected transaction costs of uncertainty are relatively low when the underlying game is of pure coordination but increase as the game attains a mixed-motive structure (chicken, assurance, prisoners dilemma etc.). 
Hard-law instruments, [O,P,D] or [O,p,D], can help curbing these problems since they have ex-ante “screening” and “ex post” constraining. First, hard law instruments entail more sunk-costs stemming from negotiation costs, ratification costs etc., which reduce the expected benefits of defection thus adding cost to the signalling – i.e. to the credibility of the IA. Secondly, because these agreements tend to lead to the production of information regarding commitment and behaviour, the expected costs of defection increase due to the the enforcement through international arbitral bodies or tribunals, due to the reputational mechanism, retaliation or domestic mechanisms of compliance (municipal judiciary or mobilization and naming and shamming by groups). Thirdly, Legalization entails a specific form of discourse, requiring justification and persuasion in terms of applicable rules and pertinent facts. Legal discourse largely disqualifies arguments based solely on interests and preferences. 
Conjectures: (i) Hard-law as commitment mechanism is expected where cooperative benefits are high and the underlying incentive structure is mixed-motive; (ii) when uncertainty regard behaviour is high; (iii) in “club goods” such as common jurisdictions or alliances, given the screening properties of hard instruments; (iv) “locking-in” hypothesis: since hard-law entails a certain degree of delegation and sovereignity costs, one would expect more hard-law when the executive wants to “lock-in” some policies and “tie the hands” of future executives or other agencies (See Moravcsik 2000). 
2.      Reducing transaction costs 
Hard law may reduce the (ex post) transaction costs in two way. From a managerial perspective, delegation of the interpretation of and day to day activities related with the IA to centralized external entities reduces the transaction costs of constantly bargaining and deciding on these matters. Even with weak delegation [O,P, d or -], high precision and high obligation may provide for the same function, as its legal nature facilitates discussion through legal modes of discourse. From an adversarial perspective, hard law instruments (specially in the form [O,P,D] or [O,p,D]) materially reduce the costs of enforcement when compared to alternatives live persuasion, or coercion – for the “demandeurs”, i.e. states that have worked to obtain commitments from others. 
Conjectures: (i) demandeurs ought to prefer hard legalization if uncertainty regarding behaviour is high, especially in mixed-motive games, and with high defection costs; (ii) when “demandeurs” which to limit participation; (iii) “demandeurs” and other incumbents share the same preferences, but other domestic actors in the country of the former (e.g. elites) have different ones (“locking-in” hypothesis again{\ldots}). 
3.      Handling the problem of incomplete contracting 
Given bounded rationality and unescapable exogenous uncertainty, states can never write IAs that anticipate every contingency. Exogenous changes may then invite opportunistic behaviour, namely due to quasi-rent capture, and consequently dissuade relation-specific welfare enhancing investments. Regimes of the form (O,p,D] are clearly designed with this purpose in mind: they utilize administrative and judicial institutions to interpret and extend broad legal principles. 
Conjecture: One can hypothesize that states will grant such authority when the anticipated gains from cooperation are large and there is reasonable consensus on general principles, but specific applications are difficult to anticipate 
Advantages of soft-law 
4.      Contracting cost 
Soft-law instruments reduce contracting costs in two ways. Firstly, given the expected lower sovereignty costs initial the negotiation costs, that is cost of arriving at an IA within everybody's preference set, become lower. Similarly, in complex and uncertain areas prone to exogenous shocks, soft legalization allows for minimizing the (expected) renegotiation costs. 
Conjecture: (i) soft legalization to reduce contracting costs ought to be more expected in agreements with high distributional problems; (ii) soft legalization to reduce renegotiation costs ought to be more expected in IAs with high uncertainty regarding the state of the world. 
5.      Sovereignty costs 
 Accepting a legally binding commitment leads to sovereignty costs to states, namely due to potential delegate drift, inferior outcomes, encroachment on state sovereignty etc. Sovereignty costs will be low if states limit their behaviour only in an ad hoc way. Greater costs will appear when delegation over relatively abstract decision-making power occurs, the largest example being the EU. Sovereignty costs are at their highest when international arrangements impinge on the relations between a state and its citizens or territory, the traditional hallmarks of (Westphalian) sovereignty. In line with this, sovereignity costs will vary greatly according to issue-area. At one extreme, sovereignty costs are especially high in areas related to national security[1]. In economic matters, sovereignity costs will tend to be negatively correlated with the technical nature of the issue; however, issues such as taxation, investment policy, money laundering etc. still entail high SC. Trade issues range between these extremes-sovereignty costs are significant but are frequently outweighed by the perceived benefits of legalized agreements. 
Conjecture: the higher the SCs the lower the softer is the legalization expected to be. 
6.      Uncertainty 
And here the authors seem to be talking about uncertainty regarding the state of the world. Namely, uncertainty meaning that because of being a new challenge or a complex one, the IA is prone to unaccounted for exogenous shock which will alter the original bargained distribution of costs and benefits. First, uncertainty about the state of the world makes precision not only desirable, as a way of increasing the flexibility of the agreement and lowering renegotiation costs, but also unattainable. A second way of reducing this uncertainty is to keep precision high but making the rules non-binding. This allows for states to obtain the benefits of the cooperation and enough flexibility to avoid the costs in case of an unaccounted for exogenous shock. Thirdly, moderate delegation, typically involving merely political and administrative bodies, provides another way for managing uncertainty as these agencies have the capacity to provide information and expertise while allowing for enough flexibility. 
Conjecture: more uncertainty regarding the state of the world, less legalization. 
7.      Soft-law as a tool of compromise 
Compromise over time – that is between patient states (low discount rates) and impatient states (high discount rate). 
Compromise between the weak and the strong – “Viewed as a process, legalization is a form of political bargaining where powerful states are advantaged. However, the efficiency gains of legalization for the powerful-cynically, providing an efficient means to extract benefits from the weak-depend on their offering the weak sufficiently satisfactory terms to induce their participation. Viewed as an outcome, legalization appears less political, since even powerful states must accept the constraints of legal principles and discourse to take advantage of legalized arrangements. Yet powerful states have the greatest influence on the substantive legal rules, and the institutions associated with (soft) international legalization are frequently constructed to ensure them a leading voice.” 



