@incollection{Boyle2013e,
abstract = {In 1919 President Woodrow Wilson famously called for a system of “open covenants..... openly arrived at.” He may not quite have lived up to his own aspirations, but the idea that international law-making should be an open and transparent process has proved a very sturdy implant. This chapter is particularly concerned with transparency as it affects international law-making. More specifically, we will consider transparency mainly from the stand-point of multilateral treaty negotiation but the points made here are equally relevant to other forms, including soft-law declarations and resolutions. At the outset it is worth asking why we should examine the principle of transparency in international law-making. At the domestic level there exists an obvious need to justify and legitimise the laws, policies, and decisions of public bodies in a democratic state accountable to the electorate. Modern legislatures are transparent insofar as they normally allow some degree of public access, and their proceedings are televised and reported by the press. One writer suggests that transparency has ‘attained quasi-religious significance in debate over governance and institutional design.' In this context the role of transparency is to contribute to democratic accountability and public participation in governance, while facilitating free speech and freedom of information about law-making and public affairs. On the international level where the interchange is primarily between States and the law-making institutions are not meaningfully democratic, it might be thought that transparency is less necessary; indeed it may even be seen as counter-productive in what is essentially a negotiating process. No negotiator would wish to reveal their position ahead of any dialogue. Some may feel it necessary to conceal their true position even after negotiations have concluded, if only to sustain illusions on both sides. Plainly, there are limits to the utility of transparency and its virtues must be balanced against other potential drawbacks. In politics, as in life, complete openness is rarely beneficial or desirable.},
annote = {a) Why it matters?

A good descriptive and normative analysis of the causes and impact of transparency in international lawmaking in general. In particular, It assesses the role of transparency in bargaining.

b) Methodology

Non-rational choice, doctrinal and historical analysis.

c) Main takeaways

Contrary to domestic politics, the case for transparency in international lawmaking involves some costs and benefits. On the cost side, transparency may make negotiations between states harder. On the benefit side, it allows form an increase in legitimacy which may facilitate compliance.

Participation in the process of international law-making

One of the mosst striking features of moder internationa law-making is the interaction and participation of states, international organizations and NGOs. The participation of the latter is particularly relevant for transparency since actors such as NGOs may difuse information on the negotiations.

However, there are few rules/principals on matters such as "who gets to participate in treaty negotiations". What we have is a set of practices which developed through time: (i) multilateral treaty-making at the UN is open to all states - so non-participation is a matter of choice and not of quality; (ii) for IOs associated with law-making, their constitutive acts tends to outline participation; (iii) NGOs have become active players in many multilateral negotiations to such an extent that in some cases such negotiations are largely driven by coalitions of NGOs and states - still, one cannot talk about a generalized right to participate; moreover, different categories of NGO status (general, special and "roster") determine the level of participation (Chinkin 1998 PROCURAR!!); among the areas of international law, the most restrictive seem to be trade law and non-proliferation law, with the WTO and the Atomic Energy Agency having extremely restrictive practices regarding NGO participation. The same applies for giving the right to "observer status to NGOs" (See pp 202-203 for a list of treaties which allow for it - most seem to be international environmental law).

Deliberative law-making process and transparency

Transparent deliberation in international law-making basically means transparent bargaining and drafting of international rules. Examples such as the negotiations of the Vienna Convention on the Law of Treaties of 1969 as well as several climate negotiations (see copenhagen, Cancun, and Durban in 2010-2011).
